erefordshire, England, United Kingdom",", Herefordshire, England.":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1165–":"circa 1165–Overleden","1210–1264":"1210–1264","1240–1302":"1240–1302","1165–Female":"1165–Overleden","1302":"1302","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","about 1165":"circa 1165","about 1240":"circa 1240","Wilton, Herefordshire, Inglaterra, United Kingdom":"Wilton, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",", Herefordshire, England.":"Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1165–":"about 1165–Deceased","1210–1264":"1210–1264","1240–1302":"1240–1302","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1302":"1302","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","about 1165":"about 1165","about 1240":"about 1240","Wilton, Herefordshire, Inglaterra, United Kingdom":"Wilton, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom",", Herefordshire, England.":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wilton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so named, including Wilton (Wiltshire, North Yorkshire), Wilton in Haile (Cumberland), and Wilton in Bridstow (Herefordshire). The North Yorkshire placename derives from Old English <i>wilde</i> ‘wild, uncultivated’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Wiltshire placename may derive from Old English <i>wull</i> ‘wool’ + <i>tūn</i>. The Cumberland and Herefordshire placenames derive from Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Wiltshire","meanings":["English: habitational name from the county of Wiltshire in southwest central England, which gets its name from   Wilton   (once the county's principal town) + Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘shire, administrative division’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan of Wilton was born about 1165, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Henry de Longchamp."},"et":{"about 1165–":"umbes 1165–Surnud","1210–1264":"1210–1264","1240–1302":"1240–1302","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1302":"1302","1210":"1210","